media.altText:
The boulders all rolled 
down the hill
on top of me, 
leaving me crushed,
all my springs uncoiled
like a snake sunbathing
on the back of a sad memory. 

Even as I'm wound back up,
by the careless hands of time,
I can feel the misfiring of valves,
my lungs puncture leaking
as I inhale restraint. 

Until I convulse 
the butterflies
from my stomach,
I'll only be 
a shadow hand 
flutter chasing 
a half light
in a halved life.

Dan Duggan

media.altText:
Sulfur

Sulfur is a key mineral in our body that helps build our DNA, make protein, protect our cells from damage, contributes to the health of skin, tendons and ligaments, and it helps in converting food into energy. Certain forms of Sulfur have shown positive effects on people with Arthritis, allergies, skin issues, and reducing the risk of diseases like Alzheimer and Parkinson’s. Sulfur deficiency can lead to skin issues, Arthritis, brittle nails and hair, depression, headaches, and gastro-intestinal issues. 

You can find Sulfur in foods like beans & lentils, nuts & seeds, dried fruits, broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower, onions, garlic, eggs, chicken, liver, and dairy products.

Here’s the rundown on #Depression…

A sense of losing something you identify with turns to Sadness. 
 
Sadness experienced for an extended amount of time(1-2 weeks+) Turns into Depression 

Full depression over time elevates physical stress in the body and manifests as ailments.
